  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering.  Here are some of the key ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention, often referred to as the Vienna Convention, was one of the first major international agreements addressing money laundering. It focused on proceeds from drug trafficking, requiring states to criminalize the laundering of drug money and to cooperate in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):**  Also known as the Palermo Convention, this treaty broadened the scope of anti-money laundering efforts to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, not just drug trafficking. It requires states to criminalize money laundering related to these crimes and to implement measures for the confiscation of proceeds.\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a treaty itself, the FATF is an inter-governmental body established in 1989 that sets international standards and promotes effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF Recommendations are recognized as the global standard. These recommendations are not legally binding in themselves, but many countries have incorporated them into their national laws and regulations, and international organizations like the IMF and World Bank use them to assess countries' compliance.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and Revised Convention (2005):** These conventions aim to facilitate international cooperation in the fight against money laundering and confiscation of criminal assets. They require participating states to criminalize money laundering and to establish effective mechanisms for identifying, tracing, freezing, and confiscating illicit proceeds. The 2005 revision expanded the scope of the original convention and strengthened international cooperation.\n\n*   **EU Directives:** The European Union has issued several directives on money laundering. These directives require EU member states to implement specific measures to prevent and combat money laundering, including customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and establishing beneficial ownership registers.\n\nThese international laws and conventions provide a framework for countries to develop and implement their own domestic anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. They also encourage international cooperation in investigations, prosecutions, and asset recovery. Because of the widespread agreement on the importance of these measures, they have become standard practice for most countries.",
